The French court rejected the proposal of the authorities of Kale to demolish dozens of home-made shops and restaurants in the Jungli camp, where thousands of refugees live.
At the court hearings this week, the authorities of Kale said that the state should be able to carry a total of 72 home-made stores, where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer to cut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or the simplest dishes for several euros in home-made restaurants.
Kale's prefecture said that these places should be demolished because they are a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and sanitary risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, saying that free dishes offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not give enough food for growing numbers in the camp.
They said that home-made shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those who need it.
The court of Lille ruled that there was no legal basis to expel people who were managing 72 home-made stores, but said that the problems of Kale prefecture "was completely clear."
Judge Jean-Fransoua Molla said that groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much greater role than just feeding people who "live in extremely shaky conditions."
He said that the spaces provided peaceful points of meeting refugees and volunteers.
One of the places that was threatened with demolition was the Jungle Book of the camp, which works for no benefit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French classes and consultations on asylum for hundreds of vulnerable minors unsusified in the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
The letter sent to the Guardian said that its closure "would be a catastrophe for these children, some of which are not older than eight years old."
Two charitable institutions, assisting Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants on Friday assessed that the number in the Jungli camp has grown and exceeded 9,000 people - the highest in history - after a sharp increase in new arrivals during the summer.
