The Russian copper company (RMC) is ready to take social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that the RMK took up the modernization of one of the oldest and most environmentally "dirty" enterprises of the country - the Karabash copper smelter.
The Karabash copper smelting plant was founded by the English Joint Stock Company led by Leslie Urquaart in 1910.
In Soviet times, this was a significant industrial enterprise for the country's economy, and it actually provided vital activity of the whole city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was stopped, which caused serious social problems in Karabash.
In 1998, it was decided to resume the work of the Karabash copper smelter.
It was also necessary to solve one of the main problems of the Karabash plant - environmental.
By the early 2000s Karabash was already infamous as an ecological disaster zone.
The situation at Karabashmedia began to change in 2004, after the company was transferred to the management of the Russian copper company.
