After the widely criticized elections last year, the governmental party and its allies completely displaced the opposition and now control the 100% of the Parliament.
At the same time, the tension along the Eritrea border is growing; the struggle for this indefinite, controversial boundary has taken hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups, which have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogagen National Liberation Front, may try to use the excitement and re-eating.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of their hearts for several years, are now flare up.
The first, it would seem, completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians were able to communicate in social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and the Internet service has become better.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized for protests.
The second is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amhara from predominantly Christian alpine areas of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of which are Muslims and live in lowlands.
But it also changes.
"We will act together under a single principle," said Mulata Hemem, the leader of Oromo.
The biggest protests took place in the districts of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that members of the Tygrai ethnic group, which is about 6% of the population, who controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics, are unjustly dominated in Ethiopia.
The third reason for the excitement is the loss of Meles Zenaoui.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, up to his death from an unknown disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts argue that he particularly skillfully recognized the first signals of dissatisfaction and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," said Abdi, an analyst with conflict situations.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Haylemariam Desalen, appeared nowhere and took the place of Melesa.
Unlike Meles, which was native to the Tygrai region in northern Ethiopia, Haylemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say that he does not enjoy the trust of the security services controlled by Tygrai.
Many fear that as a result it will lead to even more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what, as analysts said, apparently, was the elections that the government had constipationed, and then forged the results.
In the course of subsequent repression, many Protestants were killed, although in less numbers compared to the last months, and this period of unrest was relatively fast.
Development experts thanked the leaders of Ethiopia for the long-sighted development of infrastructure, such as a new long-distance train and significant success in the fight against poverty.
But it is obvious that this did not stop the growth of internal dissatisfaction with the government of Ethiopia.
And it takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, the city in Amhara, attacked enterprises belonging to Tygrai, and anti-Tygras hatred in social networks becomes comprehensive.
