NASA's climatic model: Venus was once inhabited
Venus may have been inhabited once, according to estimates of the new climatic model of NASA.
Scientists from the Usov Institute for Space Studies Goddard developed a model for the study of the past Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether it could, with its hot waterless surface and the atmosphere oversaturated with carbon dioxide, there are some conditions similar to those of the earth.
Scientists previously assumed that the small speed of the rotation of Venus was due to its dense atmosphere.
But the last modeling suggests that Venus could probably have a tense atmosphere like the earthly, and still spin slowly.
The model also considered the topography of early Venus.
On the planet, in all likelihood, there were more arid regions than on Earth, but once there was enough water and a geographical enough smanage to create conditions for life and to prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited the sun, which was 30 percent dim.
"According to the GISS model, the slow rotation of Venus substitutes for the sun for almost two months in one time," explained Anthony Del Henio, a GISS scientist in a press release.
This warms the surface of the planet and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella that protects the surface of the planet from a significant part of the solar heat.
The result is the average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are somewhat colder than nowadays on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development, which was previously assumed by specialists in the study of planets.
Despite the fact that Venus may have been inhabited, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen flirtered, only the dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly greenhouse effect remained, that is, Venus, as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
