Kepler measures the speeds of the Star in the Pleiade cluster
The last space telescope mission of Kepler helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalogue of rotational velocities of the stars included in the Pleiad cluster.
New data help astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, as well as how the rotation periods correlate with the formation of planets.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Louisa Riball, a researcher at the Center for Californian Technology Institute in a press service.
The Pleiad accumulation is located in 445 light years from the Earth.
Many stars in the cluster now only reach maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They rotate as fast as ever will no longer.
At their peak speeds these adult stars throw out large amounts of star wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of the stars, these winds have a hindrance effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its rotation speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots such as sun spots.
The latest catalogue of speeds of rotation makes us assume that more massive stars revolve more slowly than less slander the stars.
Riball compares the stars with the dancers: larger make pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the "ballet" of the Pleiad we see that those that rotate slowly, usually more massive, while those that rotate faster, usually belong to very light stars," said Riball.
Since the Pleiac cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for mapping the properties of stars with rotation speeds.
"The Star cluster of Pleiada provides a starting point for the theoretical models of rotation of the stars, both the younger and the older," Riball said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why the stars slow down the speed of their rotation and hang on the nail their "dance shoes," figuratively speaking.
Ribal and her colleagues described in detail their last analysis of the speeds of Pleiad rotation in three new articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomy magazine.
