Many have heard of the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps it was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varnanian non-cropolis, a fantastic amount of gold artifacts was found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only from one burial, known as "mighted # 43," 990 gold items with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg were extracted.
However, the official status of the world's oldest gold can soon go to the inconspicuous look of the beads found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement, known as Tell Yunaceta.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yunacite is located away from the sea, near the village of Yunacite Pazardzhik district.
Busin is a golden strip, wrapped in a ring.
Yavor Boyajiyev, the head of the excavations in Telle Yunacite, dated the discovery of 4600 BC and said that she is older than the gold of Varna for at least 200 years.
The Treasures of Varna, we recall, date back to approximately the same period, 4600 - 4200 BC.
Technology, allowing with impeccable accuracy to date metal, currently does not exist.
Where is the certainty of what gold is older?
Obviously, Professor Boyajiyev knows more than reported to Reuters: "I am absolutely sure that Yunasita's gold is older than Varna's gold."
It's a find of extreme importance: it's a tiny object, but it's big enough to take a possible place in history.
In an interview with Reuters Bojadzhiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re-and-scan study the archaeological layer, where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bead with the maximum possible accuracy.
The place of find also explains a lot.
Tell Yunaceite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Currently, Telll Yunaceite is considered the oldest "city" of Europe.
The Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in 7 millennia BC.
Over the next centuries, metal processing has been rapidly developing in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the domestic historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkan-Carpathian Metallurgical province.
In 5 millennia BC around the centers of metalworking began to arise urban settlements.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunaceta, perhaps the oldest, as here were found artifacts 4900 BC.
I would call Tell Yunacete the prototype of the modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This is a place older than Sumer for a thousand years," says Boyadzhiev, bearing in mind the generally accepted opinion that urban culture was born in the south of Mesopotamia - modern Iraq.
There were the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
The excavations of Tella Yunazite have been conducted since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists excavated almost 12 hectares, it is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall were found, which once reached three meters in height.
There is little that has survived from houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish the streets, public buildings, urban dense construction, "business center" and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunaceta is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figurines of birds were found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, from here there was an assumption that they were not decorative objects, but an object of a local cult.
The Bird City was destroyed about 4100 BC - perhaps the Indo-European tribes that came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
The three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of brutal slaughter: inside the houses were found the remains of old men, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by combat axes.
New findings and new facts appear annually, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe, which was born in the Balkans.
The "gold of Varna" found relatively recently in 1972 became a powerful stimulus in search of this civilization.
It is logical that the golden luxury of Varna had to precede something - something like a tiny gold beads created in Telle Yunacite.
